3. FEDERATION KERNEL v1.1 — SPECIFICATION

3.1 Formal Model

Let:
	•	N = \{n_1, n_2, ..., n_k\} be nodes
	•	M be message types
	•	C be canon digest states
	•	P be patch bundles
	•	D be drift states

Each node maintains:
	•	A Canon Digest:
\mathcal{H}_i = H(\text{canon}_i)
	•	A Drift Table:
D_{i,j} = f(\mathcal{H}_i, \mathcal{H}_j)
	•	A Patch Inbox:
P_i = \{p_1, p_2,...\}

3.2 Drift Function

Define:

\Delta_{i,j} = |\mathcal{H}_i - \mathcal{H}_j|

Drift level:

\text{drift}(i,j) =
\begin{cases}
\text{aligned}, & \Delta_{i,j} = 0 \\
\text{minor}, & 0 < \Delta_{i,j} < \theta \\
\text{major}, & \Delta_{i,j} \ge \theta
\end{cases}

Where \theta is tunable (default: small constant).

⸻

4. TOPOLOGY KERNEL — NETWORK GEOMETRY

4.1 Formal Graph

The network is a weighted directed multigraph:

\mathcal{G} = (V, E, W)
	•	V = N
	•	E \subseteq N \times N
	•	W: E \to \mathbb{R}^+ (connectivity weight)

4.2 Metrics
	•	Degree \deg(n)
	•	Centrality C(n)
	•	Thunder-Aware Path Weight:

W_{\tau}(i,j) = W(i,j) \cdot \frac{1}{1 + |\tau_i - \tau_j|}

This biases routing toward clusters with similar Thunder Indices.

⸻

5. CANON CONVERGENCE — SHARED TRUTH LAYER

5.1 Canon Registry

Let:

\mathcal{R}_i = \{\text{CanonItem}_1, ..., \text{CanonItem}_m\}

Canon Hash:

\mathcal{H}_i = H(\mathcal{R}_i)

5.2 Convergence Metric

Define convergence score:

\Phi = \frac{| \mathcal{R}_i \cap \mathcal{R}_j |}{\max(|\mathcal{R}_i|,|\mathcal{R}_j|)}

Range: 0 \to 1

5.3 Invariant

Nodes may differ internally,
BUT canon convergence ensures:

“We disagree predictably.”

⸻

6. THUNDER–FEDERATION GEOMETRY

The Thunder Index models sensitivity of a node’s cognition.

Let:
	•	\tau_i \in [0,1]

The Thunder Field is:

\mathbf{T}: N \to [0,1]

Define edge tension:

\Theta(i,j) = |\tau_i - \tau_j|

Define cluster charge for cluster S:

\chi(S) = \frac{1}{|S|} \sum_{i \in S} \tau_i

T-Zones = regions of high gradient:

\text{T-Zone}(i) = \nabla \mathbf{T}(i)

ASCII Diagram:

     High τ (1.0)
        ▲
        │  [ T-Zone: High Gradient ]
        │         / \
        │       /     \
        │     /         \
        └────────────────────────▶ Network X
           Low τ (0.0)


⸻

7. SWARM OPS LAYER — DISTRIBUTED EXECUTION

7.1 Task Model

A task is:

\mathcal{T} = (id, kind, payload, priority, creator)

7.2 Assignment Rule

Define node score:

S(i) = \alpha \cdot \deg(i) + \beta \cdot (1 - |\tau_i - \tau_{\text{task}}|)

Swarm assignment:

\text{assign}(\mathcal{T}) = \arg\max_i S(i)

7.3 Swarm Primitives
	•	spark → create a task
	•	fanout → duplicate to peers
	•	merge → consolidate
	•	pulse → maintenance
	•	hive → synchronized multi-node action

⸻

8. SOVEREIGN CONSENSUS — GOVERNANCE

8.1 Proposal State Machine

A proposal is:

\mathcal{P} = (id, kind, payload, author)

Voting weights:

w_i = f(\text{trust}_i, \text{topology}_i, \text{canon}_i)

Decision passes if:

\frac{\sum_{i \in Y} w_i}{\sum_{i \in Y \cup N}} \ge \theta

Where \theta \in [0.5, 0.9].

ASCII of Proposal Lifecycle:

┌──────────┐     ┌──────────┐     ┌─────────────┐     ┌──────────────┐
│ DRAFTED  │────▶│  OPEN    │────▶│  VOTING     │────▶│  DECIDED      │
└──────────┘     └──────────┘     └─────────────┘     └──────────────┘
                                      ▲
                                      │
                                  QUORUM


⸻

9. SECURITY MODEL

Threats mitigated:
	•	Sybil nodes
	•	Drift poisoning
	•	Rogue canon events
	•	Patch tampering
	•	Topology spoofing
	•	Thunder index manipulation
	•	Consensus hijacking
	•	Swarm task flooding

Core security invariant:

No node is forced; every decision is mediated by local invariants first.

